<!DOCTYPE html>
<html>
  <head>
    <title>Learn DSA</title>
    <link rel='stylesheet' href='/stylesheets/style.css' />
    <%- include('../../partials/head') %>
  </head>
  <body>

    <div class="d-flex">
      <%- include('../../partials/sidebar') %>

      <main class="flex-fill p-4">
        <div class="text-center">
          <h3>AVL Tree</h3>
        </div>
        <div class="slide active">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # What is an AVL Tree?

            An **AVL Tree** is a self-balancing Binary Search Tree (BST).

            - Named after **Adelson-Velsky and Landis**
            - Maintains balance automatically after insertions and deletions
            - Ensures efficient operations

            ####Balance Factor = height(left) - height(right)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              30-->20;
              30-->40;
              20-->10;
              20-->25;
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="slide">
          <div class="slide-content markdown">
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Balance Factor

            Each node has a **balance factor (BF)**:

            ####BF = height(left subtree) - height(right subtree)####

            AVL Tree condition:
            - BF must be **-1, 0, or 1**

            If BF is outside this range → tree becomes unbalanced

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[BF = 0]-->B[Balanced];
              C[BF = 2]-->D[Unbalanced];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Rotations in AVL Trees

            To restore balance, AVL Trees use **rotations**:

            - Left Rotation
            - Right Rotation
            - Left-Right Rotation
            - Right-Left Rotation

            These operations keep the BST property intact

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Unbalanced]-->B[Rotation];
              B-->C[Balanced];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # Example: Right Rotation

            Used when tree is **left-heavy**

            Steps:
            1. Promote left child
            2. Demote current node to right child

            ####NewRoot = LeftChild####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[30]-->B[20];
              B-->C[10];
              A-->D[40];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <div class="slide"> 
          <div class="slide-content markdown"> 
            <script type="text/markdown">
            # AVL Tree Complexity

            AVL Trees guarantee:

            - Search: **O(log n)**
            - Insert: **O(log n)**
            - Delete: **O(log n)**

            Because the tree remains balanced

            ####Height ≈ log(n)####

            mermaid
            graph TD;
              A[Balanced Tree]-->B[Fast Operations];
              B-->C[O(log n)];
            /mermaid
            </script>
          </div> 
        </div>

        <!-- CONTROLS --> 
        <div class="nav-controls"> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark me-2" id="prev">← Prev</button> 
          <button class="btn btn-outline-dark" id="next">Next →</button> 
        </div> 
        <div class="progress-container"> 
          <div class="progress-bar" id="progress"></div> 
        </div> 
        <div class="slide-counter"> 
          <span id="current">1</span>/<span id="total">1</span> 
        </div>
      </main>
    </div>
  </body>
  <script src="/javascripts/render-slides.js"></script>
</html>
